30.65 acres located at 625 Magdala Place and 6450 Apex Barbecue Road. The subject properties are identified
on Wake County Tax Maps as PIN# 0731-78-2761 and 0731-78-4176.
SAINT MARY MAGDALENE CHURCH MAJOR SITE PLAN
Prepared by: June Cowles, Senior Planner
The purpose of the public hearing is to review, hear, consider and approve, approve with conditions, or
disapprove the application for a Major Site Plan.

SAINT MARY MAGDALENE CHURCH MAJOR SITE PLAN
Prepared by: June Cowles, Senior Planner
The site includes the existing Saint Mary Magdalene Catholic School, athletic fields, and woods. The existing
site slopes gradually towards the Green at Scotts Mill subdivision to the northeast. The highest area of the site
is located within the proposed ball field and along Apex Barbecue Road.
The applicant conducted a neighborhood meeting on April 24, 2014. Please see attached Neighborhood
The applicant is proposing the addition of a 37,525 square foot church, parking, a ball field, and three retention
ponds that are located east of the existing Saint Mary Magdalene School. The proposed Saint Mary Magdalene
Church Major Site Plan provides an additional 325 parking spaces.
The site includes 7.45 acres of RCA. The RCA is comprised of woods and required buffers located
along Apex Barbecue Road, and existing buffers and proposed buffers adjacent to Green at Scotts
Mill single family residential homes to the east.
The Major Site Plan will utilize and connect to existing Town water and sewer.
The proposed Saint Mary Magdalene Major Site Plan is located in the Secondary Watershed
Protection Overlay District. The 4.84 acre parcel located in the southeast area of the site is located
in the Primary Watershed Protection Overlay District. The proposed plan includes three retention
ponds that are located within the parking lot. The proposed plan will comply with the
The proposed Major Site Plan meets all requirements of the Unified Development Ordinance.
The proposed 37,525 square foot church’s main entrance is located on the west elevation. The
building materials include red brick and a blue-gray stone as a wainscot on the columns and
portions of the building. Windows and arched frames are located on all elevations. The building
has parapet walls and standing seam roofing on the steeples/domes. The height of the church
building is 48 feet which is consistent with the UDO.
The building will include lights under the canopy and wall pack lighting above exits. Lights are
located along pedestrian pathways, at a height of 42 inches, and parking lot lights, at a height of 30
feet within the parking lot and along the entrance off of Apex Barbecue Road. As required in the

The Major Site Plan includes buffers as follows:
The UDO 8.1.2.C.6 states that Resource Conservation Area may be established in lieu of portions of
otherwise required perimeter, streetfront, thoroughfare, and highway buffers at a 1 to 1 ratio. The
Major Site Plan along Apex Barbecue Road includes a thoroughfare 30 foot wide Type “E” buffer.
The reduction to a 20 feet wide buffer is exchanged for RCA at a ratio of 1 to 1. Along the entrance
the thoroughfare buffer is a 50 foot Type “E” buffer.
The proposed buffer along the residential area includes an existing 20 foot wide Type “A” and an
additional 30 foot wide Type “B” buffer for a total of a 50 foot wide buffer.
The proposed church is providing bike racks, benches, and a multi-use field as amenities of the site.
The UDO parking requirement for the proposed church is 331 parking spaces. The Major Site Plan
includes 325 new parking spaces. The school currently has 164 existing parking spaces. Therefore,
the proposed Major Site Plan is consistent with the UDO and includes a total number of 489
The proposed Major Site Plan is consistent with the Apex Transportation Plan. The plan includes connections
with the existing church parking lot at the entrances of Townside Drive and Village Commons Lane. A new
entrance is proposed at Apex Barbecue Road.

Church traffic will be able to use all three points of access for ingress or egress.

text.b: Churchwood Drive Condition (Applicant Agrees with Condition)

page.text: Churchwood Drive is an existing stub street on an adjacent property (at Green at Scotts Mill subdivision) that is
stubbed to the church site. Typically a public street would be required to connect through the church property
to the stub street, but staff is recommending that the public vehicular turnaround be connected to the stub
street in lieu of a full public street connection. The original intent of the Churchwood stub street was to be
connected through a future subdivision to Apex Barbecue Road; the Saint Mary Magdalene site plan with the
private parking lot as proposed would prohibit that connection and leave a dead end street with no cul-de-sac
or turnaround. Staff has requested a public vehicular turnaround area at the end of Churchwood Drive that
would serve garbage trucks, fire trucks, and other service and delivery vehicles.
UDO Section 2.3.6.E.2.h “Major Site Plan”, “Applicable Standards of Article 7”, “Subdivision” requires adherence
with Section 7.2.1.A.2.c.ii regarding connection of stub streets. In staff’s opinion, the completion of the stub
SAINT MARY MAGDALENE CHURCH MAJOR SITE PLAN

August 14, 2014, the applicant agreed to the following staff-recommended condition for the Major Site
“The applicant/owner shall provide a public vehicular turnaround, with a design approved by Town of
Apex Construction Management staff, at the end of Churchwood Drive that would serve garbage trucks,
fire trucks, and other service and delivery vehicles prior to C.O.”

As currently planned, this development will consist of a 30,800 square feet church
expansion and not a school expansion. The site plan proposes one access on Apex-

DAVENPORT was retained to determine the potential traffic impacts of this
development and to identify transportation improvements that may be required to
accommodate the impacts of both background traffic and new development traffic. The
following intersections were included in the study:
• Village Commons Lane at Existing Access
• Town Side Drive at Magdala Place
• Apex-Barbecue Road at Town Side Drive

The above-mentioned intersections were analyzed for the following scenarios:
The planned build-out year for this development is 2015. A study year of 2016 (build-out
plus one year) was used for analysis purposes. The Arrival (7-9 am) and Dismissal (4-6
pm) weekday peaks were studied along with Sunday (8 am-12 pm) peak. Also the
internal circulation for school traffic was reviewed and recommendations are provided.
This Transportation Impact Analysis (TIA) was carried out based on the Town of Apex
and North Carolina Department of Transportation (NCDOT) typical standards.

14-412 St. Mary Magdalene Church – Transportation Impact Analysis
The St. Mary Magdalene Church expansion is planned will consist of a 30,800 square
feet church. TripGen 2013 software, based on the 9
Manual, was used to project trips for this development. Table 4.2 presents the results.
Site trips for this proposed expansion were distributed based on the existing traffic
patterns and engineering judgment. The trip distribution model is shown in Figure 5, and
the directional distributions for site trips are as follows:
• 60% to and from the east on Apex-Barbecue Road
• 30% to and from the west on Apex-Barbecue Road
• 5% to and from the north on Town Side Drive
• 5% to and from east on Village Commons Lane
The 2016 future no build traffic volumes were computed by applying a 2.0%
compounded annual growth rate to the 2014 existing traffic volumes. Figure 6 shows
2016 future no build traffic volumes for Arrival, Dismissal and Sunday peaks.
The proposed access will connect to existing parking lots. With the connection, it is
assumed that internal circulation for AM and PM peaks will use the proposed site
entrance on Apex-Barbecue and exit at the Magdala Place entrance. Therefore, those
trips associated with the existing development will be rerouted to the new access road.
It is assumed that the Sunday peak hour traffic will use the entrance at Apex-Barbecue
Road as well, so a percentage of background traffic trips will be rerouted.

The Transportation Research Board’s Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) utilizes a term
“level of service” to measure how traffic operates in intersections and on roadway
segments. There are currently six levels of service ranging from A to F. Level of
service “A” represents the best conditions and Level of Service “F” represents the worst.
Synchro Traffic Modeling software was used to determine the level of service for studied
intersections. Note for unsignalized intersection analysis, the level of service noted is
for the worst approach of the intersection. This is typically the left turn movement for
the side street approach, due to the number of opposing movements. All worksheet
reports from the analyses can be found in the Appendix.
